# Financial Services Consultant (Management Consulting)

## Overview
Management consultants in Financial Services practices solve complex business problems for banks, insurers, and fintech companies through strategic analysis, recommendations, and implementation support across diverse challenges.

## Core Responsibilities
- Structure complex business problems using analytical frameworks and develop data-driven insights to guide strategic recommendations for financial institutions.
- Conduct quantitative and qualitative analysis including financial modeling, market research, and competitive benchmarking to support client decision-making processes.
- Work directly with C-suite executives and board members to understand business needs, deliver recommendations, and build trusted advisory relationships throughout engagements.
- Formulate strategic recommendations on growth opportunities, market positioning, digital transformation, and business model evolution for financial services clients.
- Support implementation of recommendations through change management initiatives, capability building programs, and performance tracking to ensure sustainable impact.
- Develop deep expertise in financial services sectors including banking, insurance, asset management, fintech, and regulatory environments across multiple client engagements.

## Key Skills Required

### Technical Skills
- Advanced Excel proficiency for financial modeling, data analysis, and visualization
- PowerPoint skills for creating executive-level presentations and client deliverables
- Financial statement analysis and business case development capabilities
- Analytical frameworks and structured problem-solving methodologies

### Interpersonal Skills
- Clear written and verbal communication for client presentations and reports
- Team collaboration and leadership skills for managing project workstreams
- Professional maturity for senior executive interactions and client relationship management
- Time management and resilience under tight deadlines and changing priorities

### Industry Knowledge
- Understanding of financial services business models, economics, and competitive dynamics
- Awareness of regulatory environment including APRA, ASIC, and RBA requirements

## Work Mode

### Analytical Work (60-70%)
Excel modeling, financial analysis, market research, data synthesis, business case development, competitor benchmarking, customer segmentation analysis, building charts and visualizations for client presentations.

### Client Interaction (15-20%)
Conducting stakeholder interviews with executives and staff, facilitating workshops, leading client meetings, presenting findings to steering committees, conducting site visits to observe operations and customer interactions.

### Deliverable Development (15-20%)
Creating PowerPoint presentations, drafting reports and recommendations, building financial models, formatting materials for quality assurance, synthesizing team analysis into cohesive narratives.

### Team Collaboration (5-10%)
Daily team meetings and progress updates, brainstorming sessions with engagement teams, supporting project management workflows, providing feedback to junior consultants, contributing to team culture.

### Professional Development (Ongoing)
Reading industry publications, developing sector expertise, pursuing certifications (CFA), attending knowledge sharing sessions, contributing to thought leadership and research initiatives.

## Workplace Culture
Fast-paced, intellectually rigorous environment with high performance expectations, collaborative teams, client site work, variable hours (8:30am-7:30pm typical, extending during peak periods), travel requirements based on client location.

## Career Path
- Entry: Business Analyst (0-2 years, AU$75-95K + bonus)
- Progression: Associate (2-3 years, AU$110-150K + bonus) → Consultant (3-5 years, AU$150-200K + bonus) → Engagement Manager (5-8 years, AU$200-280K + bonus) → Partner (12+ years, AU$400-800K+ + profit share)

